Background:&nbsp;Currently&nbsp;two large randomized trials are evaluating specialty palliative care (SPC) co-management versus standard surgical care in surgical oncology patients. High-quality data support early integration of (SPC) in patients with advanced malignancy and it has been suggested that SPC referral prior to surgery may be beneficial for patients undergoing curative-intent surgical resection. In this study, we aim to evaluate surgeons&rsquo; insights, perspectives, and biases regarding early SPC referral. Specifically, we focus on surgeons that treat pancreatic cancer since this malignancy is highly lethal and surgery is associated with significant morbidity. Our hypothesis is that many surgeons will harbor significant reservations about early SPC referral and co-management.

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>: &nbsp;A qualitative investigation using 1:1 in person (or via zoom) interviews with 40 open-ended questions were conducted. Data accrual continued until theme saturation was achieved. The grounded theory approach was used for data coding and analysis.&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Results</strong>:&nbsp;A total of 9 interviews were conducted with expert pancreatic surgeons from&nbsp;5 medical centers across&nbsp;the country; 5 males and 4 females. The mean number of years in practice 18 (10-34) and the median number of pancreatic cancer cases performed per year was 55 (IQR 38-80). During preoperative counseling, all surgeons emphasize optimism, hope, and the possibility of&nbsp;cure.&nbsp;All surgeons discuss the likelihood of recurrence as well as postoperative complications, but 70% agree that patients do not fully understand these risks. 90% of surgeons do not initiate a conversation about long term outcomes and end-of-life&nbsp;care citing&nbsp;fear of taking away hope/ motivation for recovery, a perception that patients do not want to discuss this with surgeons,&nbsp;that it would send a mixed message, and time constraints.&nbsp;One surgeon utilizes SPC referral in the curative-intent setting, but only for the highest risk patients.&nbsp;All surgeons were concerned that early SPC referral may interfere with optimism/ motivation, and 30% of surgeons were concerned that SPC may discourage patients from pursuing surgery. There is also concern that SPC providers may not have an adequate understanding of pancreatic cancer therapy. Additional perceived barriers include patient and provider association of SPC with hospice and limited SPC resources.&nbsp;

Discussion:&nbsp;Pancreatic surgeons tend to use SPC intervention later in the course of the disease rather than as an early element of multimodal&nbsp;care. Surgeons are more likely to embrace early SPC if the SPC provider has an in-depth understanding of the multidisciplinary approach to pancreatic cancer. &nbsp;

BACKGROUND:&nbsp;The lymph node ratio (LNR) of nodal metastases to total harvested lymph nodes after pancreatoduodenectomy (PD) has been proposed as a prognostic factor for patients with pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC).&nbsp;We present the first study addressing&nbsp;the prognostic value of LNR in the setting of different neoadjuvant and adjuvant therapy approaches for PDAC. Understanding the influence of neoadjuvant therapy on LNR can help elucidate the treatment effect and lymph node yield in such aggressive malignancy.&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>: &nbsp;134 patients diagnosed with resectable, borderline-resectable and locally-advanced PDAC who underwent PD between 2010-2019 were identified. LNR was calculated and used to stratify patients into N0 (LNR=0), N-A (LNR 0-&le;0.1), N-B (LNR 0.1-&le;0.2) and N-C (LNR&gt;0.2) groups. Patients were categorized based on first-line treatment as: surgery first (SF), neoadjuvant therapy (NAT), and total neoadjuvant therapy (TNT).

<br><br><strong>Results</strong>:&nbsp;Utilizing LNR revealed 70 patients (52.2%), 26 (19.4%), 20 (15%) and 18 (13.4) in the N0, N-A, N-B and N-C groups, respectively. There were no statistically significant differences between groups comparing age, gender, and index cancer antigen 19-9 (CA 19-9) (p=0.053, 0.42 and 0.78, respectively). Preoperative CA19-9 differed significantly between the groups (29 vs. 68 vs. 40 vs. 318 for N0, N-A, N-B and N-C, respectively; p=0.011). The distribution of clinical stage was similar between the groups (p=0.836). However, the N0 group was associated with lower pathological stage compared to the others (p&lt;0.001). There was no difference in NAT administration across the groups, although a lower TNT administration rate trend was noted as the LNR increased (N0=50%, N-A=27%, N-B=20% and N-C=5.6%, p=0.001). There was no difference in R0 resection rate across all groups (p=0.77). The N0 group demonstrated the least median number of harvested lymph nodes (14), while N-A patients had the highest median (23) (p=0.0247). No difference in adjuvant chemotherapy was seen (p=0.069), although the N0 group received less adjuvant radiotherapy (p&lt;0.001). Patients with node-positive disease demonstrated worse overall survival (OS) compared to the N0 group (HR 1.32, 95% CI: 1.1-1.6, p=0.004), but no significant survival differences were noted between the N-A, N-B and N-C groups (p=0.813).&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Conclusions</strong>:&nbsp;As expected,&nbsp;PDAC&nbsp;patients with LNR=0 had significantly higher OS. LNR had a limited prognostic value in patients with one or more positive lymph nodes. TNT was administrated more frequently in the LNR=0 group and associated with fewer harvested lymph nodes. This is likely explained by the increased treatment response and lymph node obliteration associated with TNT approach.

INTRODUCTION&nbsp;

Intimate partner violence (IPV) describes physical, psychological, or sexual harm by a current or former partner. IPV affects an estimated 1 in 4 women and 1 in 7 men in their lifetime, and is associated with significant health sequelae. In the trauma population, the prevalence of IPV is estimated to be 11-15%. Given these statistics, the American College of Surgeons (ACS) endorses universal screening for IPV in trauma settings. However, baseline knowledge of IPV is poor among surgeons and screening is variable. We designed a project to educate surgical residents on IPV and standardize IPV screening in all trauma patients.&nbsp;

METHODS&nbsp;

A curriculum on IPV education and screening was designed using peer-reviewed literature for surgery residents rotating at a Level 1 trauma center. Residents were surveyed prior to intervention using the Modified Provider Survey, a validated instrument that assesses IPV related attitudes, beliefs, and behaviors. The education sessions took place via Zoom video calls, and focused on IPV incidence, epidemiology, and rationale for universal screening. We also provided framing language that normalized screening and disclosure of relevant reporting laws, and instructions for conducting the three-question Partner Violence Screen. An IPV survivor and trauma social worker shared stories and advice on how best to approach the topic with patients. Educational material was emailed to residents following the call and prior to the start of their trauma rotation.

RESULTS&nbsp;

Fifty seven surgical residents (64% response rate) spanning post-graduate years 1-7 completed surveys prior to receiving education. Only 4% of respondents correctly identified the prevalence of IPV. Only 6% of residents felt they had received adequate education on IPV, yet 100% believed that identifying victims of IPV was relevant to their specialty. Seventy-four percent of respondents agreed that a significant barrier to IPV screening was a lack of knowledge regarding appropriate questions. Eighty percent did not know how to respond to a positive screen, and 89% were unsure of community resources for victims.&nbsp;

CONCLUSIONS&nbsp;

IPV is a nation-wide problem affecting a significant proportion of trauma patients. A curriculum was designed and implemented in an academic general surgery residency program to address deficiencies in education regarding IPV. Although all residents considered identifying victims of IPV relevant to their career, few felt they had received adequate training in IPV and most identified lack of education as a significant barrier. Furthermore, residents vastly underestimated the societal prevalence of IPV and the majority never screened patients for IPV. These preliminary data strongly support the importance of implementing an IPV curriculum for surgical residents to enable universal screening of trauma patients. Next steps include assessing residents&rsquo; knowledge, behavior, and attitudes post-education, and tracking their screening practices.

Background: Demands for increased efficiency and direct faculty involvement in all aspects of care, threaten graduated independence in many general surgery residency programs.&nbsp;On the Chairman&rsquo;s service, chief residents are entrusted to provide the full spectrum of care in their own elective general surgery practice under attending supervision.&nbsp;We hypothesized that this educational model provides safe care for patients similar to standard services where rotating residents adopt the practices and preferences of their attending. We compared outcomes following a common operation, inguinal hernia repair, as a marker of the safety of surgical care.

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>:  The Chairman&rsquo;s Service is designed to allow chief residents to evaluate patients in their own clinic, schedule operations into their block time, and take responsibility for medical decision making. All aspects of care are properly supervised, but the resident determines the appropriateness of surgical intervention, plans the approach and performs the operation with their own preferred technique instead of practicing according to their attending&rsquo;s preferences. We retrospectively identified patients undergoing inguinal hernia repairs from July 2016 through June 2019 and matched Chariman&rsquo;s service operations to standard service operations 1:1 on CPT, sex and age. We compared patients, recurrence rates, outcomes and complications.&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Results</strong>: Chief residents performed 78 inguinal hernia repairs (66% open and 34% laparoscopic) on the Chairman&rsquo;s Service during the study period. Age, BMI and ASA were similar between the services, but Chairman&rsquo;s service patients were less likely to be current smokers (1.3% vs 24.7%) and more likely to be past smokers (59.7% vs 26.0%) than standard service patients (p&lt;0.01). Rates of incarcerated (5.2% vs 9.1%), recurrent (10.4% vs 5.2%) and bilateral hernias (19.5% vs 10.4%) were similar between the Chairman&rsquo;s service and standard services, respectively (all p&gt;0.05). Operative times were longer for the Chairman&rsquo;s service for open (123 min vs 67, p&lt;0.01) and laparoscopic (112 min vs 79, p=0.02) repairs. Recurrence rates (6.5% vs 3.9%, p=0.47) and complications including infection, seroma or hematoma requiring evacuation and need for reoperation were similarly low (p&gt;0.05) between the Chairman&rsquo;s and standard services, respectively. Despite low complication rates, Chairman&rsquo;s service patients were more likely to present to the ED post-op (14.3% vs 1.3%; p=0.001), but readmission rates were similarly low (2.6% vs 0%, p=0.09).&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Conclusions</strong>: Providing general surgery chief residents with a supervised opportunity to direct, plan and provide surgical care in clinic and the operating room, as a transition to what they might experience following graduation, is safe for patients presenting with inguinal hernias.&nbsp;Concerns about patient safety should not be a barrier to maximizing entrustment for the evaluation and operative management of select core general surgery diagnoses and operations.

Objectives: Pedestrian versus automobile accidents have become a national public health crisis representing 17% of all traffic deaths. State transportation databases have limited data regarding injury severity of pedestrian vs. automobile patients. In an effort to identify opportunities to reduce injury severity, we integrated the state transportation and trauma databases to identify the impact of signaled street crossings (SC) vs. non-signaled street crossings (NSC) on injury severity.

&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>:  Single center retrospective review of all pedestrian vs. automobile patients treated at an ACS-verified level 1 trauma center from 2014-2018 was performed. Patients were matched to state transportation database by name, gender, and date of crash. Google Earth Pro version 7.3 satellite imagery with crash-specific data was used to identify SC vs NSC. Injury severity of pedestrians struck at SC was compared to those at NSC.


<br><br><strong>Results</strong>: 512 patients were matched (mean age=41.2&plusmn;18.5 years, 74% male). Pedestrians struck at SC (n=206) had lower ISS (10.8&plusmn;10 vs. 18.9&plusmn;13.2, p&lt;0.001), hospital length of stay (3[0&ndash;73] vs. 6[0&ndash;118] days, p&lt;0.001), and mortality (21[10%] vs. 52[17%], p=0.04), as compared to those struck at NSC (n=206). Furthermore patients struck at SC had lower frequencies of sustaining an AIS &ge; 3 injury in the head (17% vs. 36%, p&lt;0.001), chest (20% vs. 36%, p&lt;0.001), abdomen (2% vs. 13%, p&lt;0.001), or extremity regions (19% vs. 36%, p&lt;0.001), compared to those &nbsp;struck at NSC.

We additionally compared the accuracy of the transportation database classification for injury severity (defined as ISS &gt;15) and morality to the trauma database. The transportation database moderately classified mortality (sensitivity = 87.7% [78.2&ndash;93.4%], specificity = 99.5% [98.4&ndash;99.9%]) and poorly classified severe injuries (sensitivity = 63.4% [55.8&ndash;70.4%], specificity = 63.4% [57.7&ndash;68.9%]).

&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Conclusions</strong>: Pedestrians struck at a SC had lower ISS and mortality compared to those at a NSC.&nbsp;The transportation database had poor correlation with actual injury severity.&nbsp; These findings demonstrate the shortcomings of transportation data alone for accurately classifying injury severity. Database integration can be used for evidence-based action-plans to reduce pedestrian morbidity and death, such as increasing the number of signaled crossings.

