Background: Low-value medical care is a significant issue in modern American medicine. Low-value preoperative care is prevalent despite the limited benefit it provides patients. Eliminating low-value preoperative care presents an important opportunity to improve value in surgery. Recent policy changes at the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services (CMS) now allow facilities and surgeons to determine the need for a preoperative H&amp;P prior to low-risk ambulatory procedures. Despite this policy change, there is little evidence to suggest that these low-value evaluations have been de-implemented. The objective is to&nbsp;identify surgeon preferences, perceived barriers and facilitators to de-implementation of routine preoperative H&amp;Ps before low-risk surgery.

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>:  We identified surgeons who perform low-risk surgeries through purposive (gender, specialty) and snowball sampling. We conducted&nbsp;phone interviews using a standardized interview guide developed using the &ldquo;Tailored Implementation for Chronic Diseases&rdquo; framework. Surgeons were asked about their understanding&nbsp;of the recent CMS policy change, and about their attitudes and current practices relating to preoperative H&amp;Ps. Interviews were audio-recorded and transcribed anonymously. Thematic coding was used to identify barriers and facilitators to de-implementation.

<br><br><strong>Results</strong>: Surgeons expressed a range of preferences regarding routine preoperative H&amp;P for patients undergoing low-risk surgery. The factors considered when planning preoperative care included risk assessment, reimbursement, patient safety, provider autonomy, and patient convenience. Most surgeons believed a preoperative H&amp;P was necessary for patient safety, however some viewed the 30-day timeline as a formality while others considered it a necessity. Some surgeons reported that they would no longer conduct an H&amp;P within the 30-day timeline if the policy were removed. Reported workflow of current preoperative care was variable with some surgeons preferring to conduct their own evaluations and others relying on outside clinics. Surgeons reported that the incentives to deescalate preoperative procedures may include patient convenience, more efficient resource allocation, and decreased provider workload. Reported barriers to de-implementing preoperative H&amp;Ps included concerns of patient safety, malpractice risks, and unexpected changes in patient health status (Table 1).

<br><br><strong>Conclusion</strong>: This study identified variations in preferences regarding routine and comprehensive preoperative H&amp;Ps prior to low-risk, ambulatory surgeries. Using these data, health systems can design strategies to de-implement low-value preoperative care in order to optimize efficiency and value in surgical care.



