Introduction

There is increasing concern regarding the attrition of surgeon-scientists in cardiothoracic (CT) surgery. However, the distinguishing characteristics of CT surgeons who lead both basic science research (BSR) and clinical research (CR) have not been previously examined in comparison to CT surgeons who only lead CR. We hypothesized that early exposure to BSR during training and active grant funding are important factors that facilitate the pursuit of BSR among practicing CT surgeons. &nbsp;

&nbsp;

Methods

We created a database of all 992 CT surgeons listed as faculty at accredited United States CT surgery teaching hospitals in 2018. Data regarding each surgeon&rsquo;s training/professional history, publication record, and National Institutes of Health (NIH) funding were acquired from publicly available online sources. Continuous data are presented as median with interquartile range and analyzed with the Mann-Whitney test. Categorical data are presented as counts with percentages and analyzed with Fisher&rsquo;s exact test.

&nbsp;

Results

Of the 992 CT surgeons in our database, 672 (67.7%) published a first- or last-author paper in 2017-2018 and were thus considered active in research. Of these 672 surgeons, 73 (10.9%) published a first- or last-author BSR paper in addition to CR in 2017-2018, while 599 (89.1%) published a first- or last-author paper only in CR in 2017-18 (Table 1). The surgeons in both groups represent a similar era (start year as an attending: 2006 [1995-2009] vs 2005 [1996-2011], respectively, p=0.403). However, only 2 women faculty in CT surgery published a first- or last-author BSR paper in 2017-2018. A similar majority of surgeons in both groups attended a top 25 NIH-funded institution during training (74.0% vs 71.8%, p=0.783) and pursued a protected research fellowship during training (69.9% vs 61.3%, p=0.162), but surgeons who are actively leading BSR are more likely to have earned a PhD degree (20.5% vs 9.7%, p=0.005), more likely to have published a first-author BSR paper during training (76.7% vs 40.9%, p&lt;0.001), and more likely to have been a co-author on a BSR paper during training (83.6% vs 58.9%, p&lt;0.001). Surgeons who are actively leading BSR are also more likely to currently be funded by an NIH grant (34.2% vs 5.8%, p&lt;0.001), especially an NIH R01 grant (21.9% vs 2.5%, p&lt;0.001).

&nbsp;

Conclusions

A great minority of CT surgeons at academic teaching hospitals are actively leading basic science research. In order to facilitate the development of future CT surgeon-scientists, additional support must be given to trainees interested in pursuing basic science research, especially among women and those who did not pursue an MD PhD degree.&nbsp;

Objectives: &nbsp;Fenestrated endovascular aneurysm repair (FEVAR) has emerged as a minimally-invasive alternative to repair complex abdominal aortic aneurysms, but direct comparisons to traditional endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR) are limited.&nbsp; Rates of 30-day readmission, time to readmission, reason for readmission, and cost after repair for FEVAR and EVAR were evaluated.&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Methods</strong>: &nbsp; Elective hospitalizations were selected from the Nationwide Readmissions Database (NRD) with longitudinal evaluation. &nbsp;ICD-9/10 procedure and diagnosis codes were identified at index hospitalization. In-hospital mortality rates, length of stay (LOS), 30-day complications, readmission rates, and charges were evaluated. Chi-square test and multivariate logistic regression were used to control for confounding.

<br><br><strong>Results</strong>:&nbsp; 23,264 EVAR and 2,374 FEVAR procedures were identified (2014-2016).&nbsp; Index mortality was similar between EVAR and FEVAR (0.14% vs. 0.14% p=.88).&nbsp; LOS was 1.7 days for EVAR vs. 1.8 days for FEVAR (p=0.12). &nbsp;FEVAR was more often performed in metropolitan areas (p &lt;.0001).&nbsp; 30-day complication rates were similar between groups including cardiac, respiratory, and renal complications. Total charges for the index stay for FEVAR were greater compared to EVAR ($125,207 vs. $114,149, p&lt;.0001).&nbsp; All cause 30?day readmission was similar for EVAR and FEVAR (13.8% vs. 14.2%, p=.87), time to readmission was similar (11.2 vs. 12.5 days, p=0.20), and readmission charges were similar ($56,101 vs. $68,918, p=0.23).&nbsp; Primary diagnosis at readmission varied between groups with the most common reason for both groups being infectious complications.&nbsp;

<br><br><strong>Conclusion</strong>: Patients undergoing FEVAR did not have increased mortality, length of stay, readmission rates, or medical complications after their procedures compared to traditional EVAR.&nbsp; Timing and rates of 30-day readmission were similar.&nbsp; FEVAR was more commonly performed in metropolitan areas and had greater overall hospital charges.&nbsp; Despite increased technical complexity of stenting visceral arteries with FEVAR, these data demonstrate that FEVAR is carries a similar complication and readmission rate to traditional EVAR.&nbsp; Further investigation into causes and prevention for the overall 30-day admission rates are needed for both procedures.
